==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interval
<hw>In"ter*val</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>intervallum</ets>; <ets>inter</ets> between + <ets>vallum</ets> a
wall: cf. F. <ets>intervalle</ets>. See <er>Wall</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A space between things; a void space intervening
between any two objects; <as>as, an <ex>interval</ex> between two houses
or hills</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'Twixt host and host but narrow space was left,⟦br⟧
A dreadful <qex>interval</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Space of time between any two points or events;
<as>as, the <ex>interval</ex> between the death of <person>Charles
I.</person> of England, and the accession of <person>Charles
II.</person></as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A brief space of time between the recurrence of
similar conditions or states; <as>as, the <ex>interval</ex> between
paroxysms of pain; <ex>intervals</ex> of sanity or
delirium.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Difference in pitch between any
two tones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At intervals</b></col>, <cd>coming or happening with
intervals between; now and then.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧And Miriam watch'd and
dozed <xex>at intervals</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Tennyson.</au> --
<col><b>Augmented interval</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>an interval
increased by half a step or half a tone.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Intervale</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Interval</ent>⟦br⟧
